        <div class="blog-article-body">

            <p class="blog-lead">
                Scanned PDFs are essentially photographs of pages. You can view
                them but you can't search, select, or copy any text. OCR
                (Optical Character Recognition) reads the text from the image
                and adds a searchable text layer where recognition succeeds.
            </p>

            <h2>What's the difference between a scanned PDF and a regular PDF?</h2>
            <p>
                A regular PDF — created from Word, Excel, or any software —
                contains actual text data. You can click on a word, select it,
                copy it, and search with Ctrl+F.
            </p>
            <p>
                A scanned PDF is different. Someone placed a physical document
                on a scanner (or photographed it), and the result is an image
                embedded in a PDF container. The PDF looks like a document but
                contains no searchable text — just pixels.
            </p>
            <p>
                You can tell the difference easily: try to click and drag to
                select text. If you can't select anything, it's a scanned PDF.
            </p>

            <h2>What is OCR and how does it work?</h2>
            <p>
                OCR stands for Optical Character Recognition. It's technology
                that analyzes an image, identifies the shapes of letters and
                numbers, and converts them into actual text data.
            </p>
            <p>
                Modern OCR engines like Tesseract (which powers PdfToolStack's
                OCR tool) are extremely accurate on clean, high-contrast scans.
                They work on printed text in dozens of languages including
                English, French, German, Spanish, Italian, Portuguese, Chinese,
                Japanese, and Arabic.
            </p>
            <p>
                After OCR, the document looks identical — the original scan is
                still displayed — but a hidden text layer is added underneath,
                making all the text searchable and selectable.
            </p>

            <h2>Step-by-step: Make a scanned PDF searchable</h2>
            <ol>
                <li>Go to <a href="/pdf-ocr">PdfToolStack PDF OCR</a></li>
                <li>Select your document language (default is English)</li>
                <li>Upload your scanned PDF</li>
                <li>Click <strong>Make Searchable with OCR</strong></li>
                <li>Wait 30-60 seconds — OCR processes each page individually</li>
                <li>Download your searchable PDF</li>
                <li>Open it and test — press Ctrl+F and search for a word</li>
            </ol>

            <h2>Tips for best OCR results</h2>
            <p>
                OCR accuracy depends heavily on the quality of your scan.
                Here's how to get the best results:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Use 300 DPI or higher when scanning</strong> — lower
                    resolution scans produce blurry text that's hard for OCR to read
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Scan in black and white for text documents</strong> —
                    color scans of text documents are larger files with no accuracy benefit
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Keep pages flat and straight</strong> — skewed or
                    curved pages reduce accuracy significantly
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Good lighting for phone scans</strong> — if you're
                    photographing a document with your phone, use plenty of light
                    and avoid shadows across the page
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Select the correct language</strong> — OCR accuracy
                    drops significantly if the wrong language is selected
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h2>When OCR doesn't work well</h2>
            <p>
                OCR has limitations. It struggles with:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Handwritten text — OCR is designed for printed text</li>
                <li>Very low resolution scans (under 150 DPI)</li>
                <li>Documents with heavy watermarks over the text</li>
                <li>Badly damaged or faded documents</li>
                <li>Complex layouts with overlapping columns and images</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                For handwritten documents, there's no reliable automated solution
                — manual transcription or specialist handwriting recognition
                software is required.
            </p>

            <h2>Common use cases for PDF OCR</h2>
            <p>
                OCR is useful in many professional contexts:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Legal:</strong> Making scanned case files and
                    old contracts searchable for discovery and review
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Accounting:</strong> Processing paper invoices and
                    receipts — OCR first, then AI extraction
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>HR:</strong> Digitizing paper employee records
                    and making them searchable
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Real estate:</strong> Processing scanned property
                    documents, title deeds, and historical records
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Healthcare:</strong> Digitizing paper patient records
                    for electronic health record systems
                </li>
            </ul>

